azettelive.co.uk/whats-on/shopping/gallery/boyes-store-middlesbrough-14815116 |website=Teesside Live|accessdate=3 January 2020}}\n\n{{varietyStores}}\n{{Scarborough, North Yorkshire}}\n\n[[Category:Department stores of the United Kingdom|Boyes]]\n[[Category:Retail companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Retail companies of England]]\n[[Category:Discount shops of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Carpet retailers of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Furniture retailers of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Variety stores]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1881]]\n[[Category:1881 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:British companies established in 1881]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Eastfield, North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Scarborough, North Yorkshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|Boyes}}\n{{Short description|Chain of department stores in England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name     = '''W Boyes & Co. Ltd'''\n| logo     = Boyes (retailer) logo.png\n| foundation       = {{start date and age|df=yes|1881}} <br />[[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]], [[North Yorkshire]], England\n| type     = [[Private company|Private]]\n| founder  = William Boyes\n| key_people = Andrew Boyes <small>([[chairman]], Joint [[Managing Director]])</small><br> Richard Boyes <small>(Joint [[Managing Director]])</small>\n| location         = [[Eastfield, North Yorkshire|Eastfield]], [[North Yorkshire]], England\n| locations        = 67 (September 2019)\n| industry         = [[Retail]] \n| products         = [[variety store|Variety]]\n| revenue          =\n| operating_income =\n| homepage         = [http://www.boyes.co.uk/ www.boyes.co.uk]\n}}\n\n'''Boyes''' is a chain of [[department stores]] in [[England]]. William Boyes founded the firm in 1881 in [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]], [[North Yorkshire]] and it has been run by generations of the Boyes family ever since.\n\nThe company's slogan is \"for good value\" and the stores specialise in the discount retail sector, stocking a mixture of regular lines, one off special purchases and clearance items. Boyes stores stock over 30,000 products over a large range including household products, fashion and footwear.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web |title=Boyes - Business to Business |url=https://www.boyes.co.uk/about-business-to-business/ |website=www.boyes.co.uk |accessdate=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIts full trading name is '''W Boyes and Co. Ltd''', however the stores trade as \"Boyes\" (pronounced Boys but often mispronounced as Boys-es).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Robinson |first1=Hannah |title=The Hull areas people seem to always mispronounce and the history behind them |date=10 August 2019|url=https://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/news/hull-east-yorkshire-news/hull-areas-people-mispronounce-history-3192406 |website=[[Hull Daily Mail]] |accessdate=13 November 2019}}</ref> It is still owned and family run with Andrew Boyes and his son Richard as joint managing directors. Richard represents the fifth generation of the family.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/boyes-expands-but-sticks-with-tradition-1-4605246|title=Boyes expands but sticks with tradition|date=1 June 2012|newspaper=[[The Yorkshire Post]]|accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe company is based at its head office at Havers Hill in [[Eastfield, North Yorkshire|Eastfield]]. It expanded this site with the purchase of the former Polestar Greaves factory in 2011. It also has a warehouse site at nearby Hopper Hill.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web |title=Scarborough family firm expands |url=https://www.thescarboroughnews.co.uk/business/scarborough-family-firm-expands-1-3411406 |website=[[The Scarborough News]] |accessdate=20 November 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028225335/https://www.thescarboroughnews.co.uk/business/scarborough-family-firm-expands-1-3411406 |archivedate=28 October 2019 |date=25 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe stores serve around 250,000 customers a week. They run a twice yearly sale and hold other promotional events.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Edwards |first1=John |title=Boyes sale in Scarborough - see 15 photos from down the years |url=https://www.thescarboroughnews.co.uk/news/boyes-sale-scarborough-see-15-photos-down-years-144208 |website=[[The Scarborough News]] |accessdate=23 November 2019 |date=30 January 2019}}</ref> \n[[File:Boyes warehouse on Havers Hill, Cayton (geograph 4811287).jpg|thumb|Boyes warehouse, Eastfield]]\n\n==History==\n\n===Scarborough===\n\n[[File:Boyes business premises, Queen Street (geograph 2391439).jpg|thumb|left|Boyes, Queen Street, Scarborough]]\nFounder William Boyes was born in 1859 and started his career as an apprentice draper with a firm called George and Collings. At the end of his apprenticeship, saving \u00a310 from his wages he opened his first store at the corner of Eastborough and Globe Street in [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]], selling remnants from merchants. The area was full of poverty, and the store was therefore popular with [[housewives]].\n\nTrade increased and William needed bigger premises to operate. Two corner units on Market Street and Queen Street were purchased in 1886. Further buildings were acquired and within ten years almost all of one side of Market Street was owned by Boyes. The store was named \u201cThe Remnant Warehouse\u201d and is still known as the Rem by older residents of Scarborough.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://imfromyorkshire.uk.com/made-in-yorkshire-volume-25-boyes/|title=Boyes - Made in Yorkshire - Volume 25|date=26 August 2015|website=I'm From Yorkshire|accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref> In 1900 Boyes became a limited company when William and three friends, James Pirie, Henry Merrie Cross and JH Harrison invested in the business.<ref>{{cite web |title=Buying well, selling cheap still pays off |url=https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/6951008.buying-well-selling-cheap-still-pays-off/|date=24 May 2015|website=[[The Northern Echo]] |accessdate=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nOver the years William added more products to the range and the store went from a warehouse to a department store.<ref>{{cite web |title=Boyes History |url=https://www.boyes.co.uk/boyes-history/ |website=www.boyes.co.uk |accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref> The company began to expand to [[York]], [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]] and [[Grimsby]] in the following years. Stores in [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] and [[North Shields]] were also opened, but closed in the [[Great Depression]].\n\nOn 26 February 1915, the store was destroyed by a huge fire, which is believed to be the biggest in Scarborough's history. It caused around \u00a370,000 of damage. The store was insured and it was rebuilt.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stephenson |first1=Susan |title=Blaze 100 Years On... |url=https://www.pressreader.com/uk/the-scarborough-news/20150226/284163629426544|date=26 February 2015|website=[[The Scarborough News]] |accessdate=4 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Scarborough store was home to a number of animals in the past, including monkeys, chipmunks and budgies.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Berry |first1=Dave |title=Jean Sidebottom spent most of her childhood moving between relatives in Scarborough and Scotland. She is the longest-serving member of staff and remembers a powerful monkey running riot in the store. |url=https://www.pressreader.com/uk/the-scarborough-news/20120124/283089886033637 |website=[[The Scarborough News]] |date=24 January 2012 |accessdate=15 November 2019}}</ref> The animals were used as way of encouraging customers to visit the store and purchase something whilst they visited. Two of the monkeys, Jacko and Dinah, are famous to a generation of Scarborough shoppers.\n\nThe Scarborough store served as Boyes head office until the site at Eastfield opened in 1971.<ref>{{cite web |title=Malcolm\u2019s happy life in great place to grow up |url=https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:9o0My8OoUxMJ:https://www.thescarboroughnews.co.uk/news/malcolm-s-happy-life-in-great-place-to-grow-up-1-1437964+&cd=29&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=uk |website=[[The Scarborough News]]|date=8 December 2008|accessdate=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Hull===\n\n;Hessle Road\n\n[[File:Boyes store on Hessle Road, Hull (geograph 5685398).jpg|thumb|Boyes, Hessle Road, Hull]]\nBoyes operated in [[Kingston upon Hull]] from 1898 with a shop in Prospect Street, but it was closed in 1901 when the lease was sold to Taylor\u2019s Drug Store, a business owned by another Boyes director, William Taylor Mason. In 1920 they returned to Hull, this time on Hessle Road. The company leased a building owned by Johnny Wardell, later buying the lease.<ref>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104191634/http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Boyes-prepares-famous-Big-Sale-hopes-new-store/story-22840959-detail/story.html | title=Boyes prepares for a famous 'Big Sale' and hopes new store will help rejuvenate Whitefriargate | newspaper=[[Hull Daily Mail]] | url=http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Boyes-prepares-famous-Big-Sale-hopes-new-store/story-22840959-detail/story.html | date=28 August 2014 | archivedate=4 January 2015|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> In 1927 Boyes bought a neighbouring property to extend the store and further extended the store in the 1950s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hullwebs.co.uk/content/l-20c/city/hessle-rd/1920.htm|title=The Growth of Hessle Road - 1920 to 1940|website=www.hullwebs.co.uk|accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n;Holderness Road\n\n[[File:Boyes on Holderness Road, Hull (geograph 3270483).jpg|thumb|Boyes, Holderness Road, Hull]]\n[[File:Boyes Plaque (geograph 1986463).jpg|thumb|Plaque outside Boyes, Holderness Road, Hull]]\nThe next store in Hull opened on Holderness Road in 1965. The store was built on the site of the former Savoy cinema. The cinema was bombed in the last [[Luftwaffe]] attack of [[World War II]] to cause civilian casualties in the UK. Thirteen people were killed and 22 injured and they are commemorated on a plaque on the outside of the store.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hullvalley.blogspot.com/2013/06/boyes.html|title=Hull and Hereabouts: Boyes|date=29 June 2013|accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Hull Blitz's last victims remembered 70 years on |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-humber-31919031 |website=[[BBC News]]|date=17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n;Bransholme\n\nA store in the [[Bransholme]] (now North Point) centre followed in 1973. Boyes were the first company to sign up to open a store in the centre.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://northpointshoppingcentre.co.uk/stores/store-details/boyes|title=Boyes|publisher=North Point Shopping Centre|accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref> The Bransholme store was under threat of closure in 2014 when terms on a new lease could not be agreed and the company began looking for new premises in Hull. After negotiations, a new lease was agreed, but Boyes still pushed on with plans for a new store.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Young |first1=Angus |title=Boyes to stay on Bransholme after jobs scare \u2013 and will open in Whitefriargate, Hull city centre |url=http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Boyes-stay-Bransholme-jobs-scare-8211-open/story-22810105-detail/story.html |website=Hull Daily Mail |accessdate=19 November 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104205325/http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Boyes-stay-Bransholme-jobs-scare-8211-open/story-22810105-detail/story.html |archivedate=4 January 2015 |date=23 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n;Whitefriargate\n\nThe company's fourth store in Hull, on Whitefriargate opened on 19 September 2014. The unit was previously occupied by [[Peacocks (clothing)|Peacocks]], and before this it was one of the first [[Woolworths Group|Woolworths]] stores in the UK.<ref>{{cite web |title=Boyes to open store in Whitefriargate, Hull |url=http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Boyes-open-store-Whitefriargate-Hull/story-21124763-detail/story.html |website=[[Hull Daily Mail]]|accessdate=19 November 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150106092743/http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Boyes-open-store-Whitefriargate-Hull/story-21124763-detail/story.html |archivedate=6 January 2015 |date=23 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Hull - Store 6 - Woolies Buildings - Then and Now |url=https://wooliesbuildings.wordpress.com/2018/04/13/hull-store-6/ |website=wooliesbuildings.wordpress.com |accessdate=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===York===\n\n[[File:Fire on Ouse Bridge, York. YORYM-S1009.jpg|thumb|Fire at Boyes, Ouse Bridge, York]]\nBoyes opened in [[York]] in 1906, on Bridge Street near the [[River Ouse, Yorkshire|River Ouse]] in a former paint warehouse. The store was destroyed by fire on 8 December 1910. The fire was thought to have begun in the toy department when gas lamps came into contact with Christmas decorations. The fire took six hours to put out, but all staff and customers were safely evacuated. Boyes moved temporarily to Clifford Street whilst their premises were being rebuilt. The fire is estimated to have caused \u00a320,000 of damage.\n\nThere was a delay to the rebuilding of the store in a tragic accident in February 1912. A workman was killed and seven others injured when a clock tower being built collapsed. The store reopened without a clock tower in December 1912.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.yorkpress.co.uk/news/15026141.amazing-photos-from-1912-of-the-rebuilding-of-the-boyes-store-gutted-by-fire/|title=Amazing photos from 1912 of the rebuilding of the Boyes store gutted by fire...|newspaper=[[The Press (York)]]|date=16 January 2017|accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe building was extended in 1966, and plans were made for it to be modernised in 1978. However, these plans were not viable and the store closed on 26 February 1983. Boyes returned to York on 15 May 1987 with a smaller store on Goodramgate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.minsterfm.com/vp/-/news/-/lifestyle/2284693/boyes-in-york-celebrates-their-30th-anniversary/|title=Boyes in York celebrates their 30th Anniversary|date=11 May 2017|publisher=[[Minster FM]]|accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref> Another store within the York city area was opened in [[Acomb, North Yorkshire|Acomb]], in April 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.minsterfm.com/news/local/1595461/listen-new-boyes-store-opened-in-acomb/|title=LISTEN: New Boyes Store Opened in Acomb|date=24 April 2015|publisher=[[Minster FM]]|accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Grimsby===\n\nThe firm established a presence in [[Grimsby]] in 1926 when the Hewlands store on Freeman Street was purchased by Boyes after the owner, Ernest Hewland got into financial difficulties. The store continued to trade under the Hewlands name until 1956 when Mr Hewland retired. The building was replaced with a new property on the same site and went by the Boyes name.\n\nThe store traded well and 1958 Boyes purchased five old properties further down Freeman Street and built a second store in their place. This store opened in May 1961. Boyes traded from both sites until the newer site was extended and reopened in October 1974 and the original Hewlands site was sold.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/grimsby-s-iconic-boyes-store-celebrates-60-years-of-successful-trading/story-29610371-detail/story.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812193402/https://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/grimsby-s-iconic-boyes-store-celebrates-60-years-of-successful-trading/story-29610371-detail/story.html|archivedate=12 August 2016|title=Grimsby's iconic Boyes store celebrates 60 years of successful trading |newspaper= [[Grimsby Telegraph]]|date=12 August 2016|accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref> A store in neighbouring [[Cleethorpes]] was opened in 2010 in a former [[Woolworths Group|Woolworths]] branch.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/whats-on/shopping/10-years-after-woolworths-collapse-2243992|title=Memories of Woolworths 10 years after its collapse|date=21 November 2018|accessdate=28 October 2019|newspaper=[[Grimsby Telegraph]]}}</ref>\n\n===Further expansion===\n\nBoyes opened stores in [[Billingham]] in 1967, [[Darlington]] in 1970<ref>{{cite web |title=A fitting finale as carpet man retires |url=https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/6957295.a-fitting-finale-as-carpet-man-retires/ |website=[[The Northern Echo]]|date=28 March 2005|accessdate=15 November 2019}}</ref> and [[Louth, Lincolnshire|Louth]] in 1976.<ref>{{cite web |title=Topless Drapers 1882 1975 - a nostalgic memory of Louth |url=https://www.francisfrith.com/louth/topliss-drapers-1882-1975_memory-871 |website=Francis Firth |accessdate=16 November 2019}}</ref> The tenth store in [[Northallerton]] opened in 1977.<ref>{{cite web |title=Store wins award for disabled recruitment |url=https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/7128194.store-wins-award-for-disabled-recruitment/ |website=[[The Northern Echo]]|date=16 October 2000|accessdate=16 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Boyes, Bridlington (geograph 3185906).jpg|thumb|left|Boyes, King Street, Bridlington]]\nThe company then developed a chain of stores throughout [[Northern England]] in the following decades.\nA store was opened in Bridlington in 1998 which has a museum with artefacts from the firm's history as well as a recreation of a till point from the start of the 20th century.<ref>{{cite web |title=Grassroots: Redcar |url=https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/7069516.grassroots-redcar/ |website=[[The Northern Echo]] |date=24 June 2002|accessdate=16 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Boyes Museum Bridlington |url=http://www.cashrailway.co.uk/photos/bridlington.htm |website=The Cash Railway Website |accessdate=16 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe company's first store in [[West Yorkshire]], in [[Bradford]], opened in 2003. Boyes took over the former [[Christopher Pratts]] store in North Parade after Pratts relocated to [[Leeds]]. At the time the company invested more than \u00a3500,000 to refurbish the store before opening and the store was one of the biggest in the chain. The company opened a small section of the store earlier in 2003 before a full opening in September.<ref>{{cite web |title=New store provides \u2018impetus\u2019 for city |url=https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/8009440.new-store-provides-impetus-for-city/ |website=Bradford Telegraph and Argus |accessdate=8 February 2020 |date=22 September 2003}}</ref> In 2019 the store relocated from North Parade to the Kirkgate Centre. The North Parade site had become unviable with the company citing factors including the closure of the city centre [[Morrisons]] store and the planned relocation of the market in the area. Boyes took over the former [[Argos]] unit in the centre.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/news/17443981.boyes-to-move-from-north-parade-to-kirkgate-shopping-centre/|title=Boyes to move from North Parade to Kirkgate Shopping Centre|newspaper=[[Telegraph and Argus]]|date=19 February 2019|accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nBoyes has expanded its reach further by opening several stores in the East Midlands and as far south as Cambridgeshire. The company reached its landmark 50th store with the opening of the [[Coalville]] store in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Burnett|first1=Clare|title=130-year-old Yorkshire retail chain expands with 2 new stores in the Midlands|url=https://bdaily.co.uk/hospitality/10-03-2014/130-year-old-yorkshire-retail-chain-expands-with-2-new-stores-in-the-midlands/|work=BDaily|date=10 March 2014|accessdate=8 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe company has increased store numbers in many cases by moving into units vacated by other retailers. They have taken over ex-Woolworths stores in Cleethorpes, [[Bishop Auckland]] and Coalville. Former Co-op department stores in [[Brighouse]], [[Ilkley]], [[March, Cambridgeshire|March]] and [[Ripley, Derbyshire|Ripley]] have been taken over, and a couple of vacated Marks and Spencer stores in [[Grantham]] and [[South Shields]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Soult |first1=Graham |title=Five years on from Woolies\u2019 collapse, Boyes signs for the Coalville store |url=https://www.soultsretailview.co.uk/2013/11/26/five-years-on-from-woolies-collapse-boyes-signs-for-the-coalville-store/ |website=Soult\u2019s Retail View |accessdate=29 November 2019 |date=26 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn recent years the company has relocated some of its branches to new locations in the same town. As well as the Bradford relocation, in 2017 the [[Gainsborough, Lincolnshire|Gainsborough]] store was relocated due to the original one being demolished for the building of a new [[Lidl]] supermarket. Boyes now trade from a newly built unit on the site of the former Crown House.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Harrison-Barker |first1=Sarah |title=Gainsborough store leaves staff in limbo after being given notice to vacate |url=https://lincolnshirereporter.co.uk/2016/09/gainsborough-store-leaves-staff-limbo-given-notice-vacate/ |website=Lincolnshire Reporter |accessdate=20 November 2019 |date=9 September 2016}}</ref> In 2018 the [[Middlesbrough]] store moved from the Dundas Centre to the Hill Street Centre, moving into a former Argos outlet.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Love |first1=Laura |title=First look inside Boyes as new branch opens inside former Middlesbrough Argos store |url=https://www.gazettelive.co.uk/whats-on/shopping/first-look-inside-boyes-new-14812253 |website=gazettelive.co.uk|date=22 June 2018|accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nStore numbers reached 67 in September 2019 with the opening of a store in [[Barton-upon-Humber]], the first to be adorned with the new company logo.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/news/local-news/new-boyes-store-opens-barton-3369480|title=New Boyes store opens in Barton in former Lidl building|date=28 September 2019|accessdate=28 October 2019|work=[[Grimsby Telegraph]]}}</ref>\n\n==Business operations==\n\nThe stores are organised in different departments and have a large range of different products including [[toys]], [[stationery]], [[toiletries]], [[housewares]], electrical appliances, [[DIY]] items, [[fishing tackle]], model making, soft furnishings, dress fabrics, [[knitting yarn]], [[haberdashery]], crafts, [[confectionery]], pet products and babywear.<ref name=\"auto3\"/> They also have a large range of clothing and footwear with ranges for men, ladies and children. Some of their larger stores also have a [[carpet]] and [[furniture]] department. Two branches at [[Bridlington]] and [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]] also have a [[caf\u00e9|cafe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boyes.co.uk/the-cafe-menu/|title=The Cafe Menu|website=www.boyes.co.uk|accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt has a presence on social media, with accounts on [[Facebook]], [[Twitter]] and [[Instagram]]. The company supports a number of local causes and is a sponsor of [[Scarborough Cricket Club (England)|Scarborough Cricket Club]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Commercial - Scarborough Cricket Club |url=https://scarboroughcricketclub.co.uk/commercial |website=Scarborough Cricket Club |accessdate=15 November 2019}}</ref> In February 2012 company directors Andrew Boyes and Timothy Boyes were given Freedom of the [[Borough of Scarborough]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thescarboroughnews.co.uk/news/people/boxer-ingle-and-four-others-honoured-by-the-town-1-4262978|title=Boxer Ingle and four others honoured by the town|newspaper=The Scarborough News|accessdate=8 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Scarborough store is part of a long standing tradition in the town each year. [[Father Christmas]] arrives on a boat in the harbour and after a parade through the town, is resident in a [[Christmas grotto|grotto]] in the store until [[Christmas Eve]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Macdonald |first1=Corinne |title=Take a sneak peek into Santa\u2019s Grotto at Boyes in Scarborough |url=https://www.thescarboroughnews.co.uk/news/people/take-sneak-peek-santas-grotto-boyes-scarborough-999408 |website=[[The Scarborough News]] |accessdate=3 January 2020 |date=15 November 2019}}</ref> The grotto and window displays have a different theme each year.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Macdonald |first1=Corinne |title=Look back at Scarborough Boyes Christmas windows through the years with these photos |url=https://www.thescarboroughnews.co.uk/news/people/look-back-scarborough-boyes-christmas-windows-through-years-these-photos-1332690? |website=[[The Scarborough News]] |accessdate=3 January 2020 |date=4 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Whitby - Boyes department store (geograph 6266424).jpg|Boyes, Station Square, Whitby\nFile:W Boyes & Co - Wednesday Market (geograph 2429887).jpg|Boyes, Wednesday Market, Beverley\nFile:Boyes - North Parade - geograph.org.uk - 1545973.jpg|Boyes, North Parade, Bradford (closed 2019)\nFile:Boyes, Swadford St (geograph 4700416).jpg|Boyes, Swadford Street, Skipton\nFile:Boyesbartonstore.jpg|Boyes, High Street, Barton-upon-Humber, September 2019\n</gallery>\n\n==Store locations==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Location !! Opened !! Notes\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align: left;\" | '''[[Cambridgeshire]]'''\n|-\n| [[March, Cambridgeshire|March]] || November 2011<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cambstimes.co.uk/news/boye-d-at-opening-manager-welcomes-customers-to-new-store-in-march-1-1136832|title=Boye-d at opening: Manager welcomes customers to new store in March|newspaper=Cambs Times|date=25 November 2011|accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref> || \n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align: left;\" | '''[[County Durham]]'''\n|-\n| [[Barnard Castle]] || 1983<ref>{{cite web |title=Store celebrates 10 busy and successful years |url=http://teesdalemercuryarchive.org/pdf/1993/October-13/October-13-1993-09.pdf |website=[[Teesdale Mercury]] |date=13 October 1993|accessdate=15 November 2019}}</ref> ||\n|-\n| [[Billingham]] || 1967 || with carpet and furn